    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "<|channel>thought\n<channel|>That makes sense. I've heard that things can get blocked up in there sometimes. Like, what actually happens if something gets inside the tube? What kind of stuff causes issues with the readings?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you've touched on a common pitfall in the world of aviation, much like a mischievous goblin hiding in the bushes. If something gets inside the pitot tube, it's like a tiny goblin blocking the path of the air. This could be debris, ice, or even bugs, which are the bane of pilots' existence. When the pitot tube gets blocked, the air can't rush into it properly, and the pressure inside the tube doesn't match the outside air pressure. This mismatch causes the airspeed indicator to give false readings, which can be as misleading as a goblin's riddle. The pilot might think they're flying at a safe speed when they're actually zooming through the sky at breakneck speed, or vice versa. It's crucial to keep the pitot tube clear, so the pilot always has a true sense of the plane's speed, just like keeping a clear path for your trusty old friend to always guide you right.",
